<exercises component="proteus" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="proteus-5-3">
<title>PROTEUS exercises (for Section 5.3)</title>
<introduction>
    <p>
        Each of the following expressions is the result of the Chain Rule being applied to a composite function. In other words, it is the right-hand side of the Chain Rule:
        <me>
            \dfrac{d}{dx} \left[ F(g(x)) \right] = F'(g(x)) g'(x) = f(g(x)) g'(x)
        </me>,
        OR, Eyerusalem requested to see what it looks like, version 2:
        <me>
            \dfrac{d}{dx} \left[ F(g(x)) \right] = f(g(x)) g'(x)
        </me>
        where <m>F(x)</m> is an antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>, so that <m>F'(x) = f(x)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        In each of the problems below, your job is to identify the functions <m>f</m>, <m>g</m>, and <m>g'</m>, recover the antiderivative <m>F</m>, and then calculate the original composite function <m>F(g(x))</m>.
    </p>
</introduction>
<exercise xml:id="proteus-5-3-matching-1" label="proteus-5-3-matching-1">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <me>
                2 (2x+5)^7 = f(g(x)) g'(x)
            </me>
            Drag the cards from the left column into the correct labels in the right column.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <cardsort>
        <match>
            <premise><m>2x+5</m></premise>
            <response><m>g(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>2</m></premise>
            <response><m>g'(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>x^7</m></premise>
            <response><m>f(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>\frac{1}{8} x^8</m></premise>
            <response><m>F(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>\frac{1}{8}(2x+5)^8</m></premise>
            <response><m>F(g(x))</m></response>
        </match>
    </cardsort>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="proteus-5-3-matching-2" label="proteus-5-3-matching-2">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <me>
                \sin(2^x) 2^x \ln(2)= f(g(x)) g'(x)
            </me>
            Drag the cards from the left column into the correct labels in the right column.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <cardsort>
        <match>
            <premise><m>2^x</m></premise>
            <response><m>g(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>2^x \ln(2)</m></premise>
            <response><m>g'(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>\sin(x)</m></premise>
            <response><m>f(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>-\cos(x)</m></premise>
            <response><m>F(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>-\cos(2^x)</m></premise>
            <response><m>F(g(x))</m></response>
        </match>
    </cardsort>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="proteus-5-3-matching-3" label="proteus-5-3-matching-3">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <me>
                3x^2 \sqrt{x^3+2} = f (g(x) ) g'(x)
            </me>
            Drag the cards from the left column into the correct labels in the right column.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <cardsort>
        <match>
            <premise><m>x^3+2</m></premise>
            <response><m>g(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>3x^2</m></premise>
            <response><m>g'(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>\sqrt{x}</m></premise>
            <response><m>f(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>\frac{2}{3}x^{3/2}</m></premise>
            <response><m>F(x)</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise><m>\frac{2}{3}(x^3+2)^{3/2}</m></premise>
            <response><m>F(g(x))</m></response>
        </match>
    </cardsort>
</exercise>
</exercises>